// ══ Key2MD Practice Stations ══

const STATIONS=[
{category:"Conflict Resolution",scenario:"You are a housemate. Stan, your university housemate, has recently decided to adopt a vegan diet. He has become passionate about being vegan, and loves talking about his reduced carbon footprint and contribution to animal welfare. At your latest dinner, Stan stated that he doesn't feel right about living in a house where animal products are regularly bought and used. He feels so strongly about this that he offers to do all the grocery shopping and cooking for everyone if you will all agree to no longer bring animal products into the house. Otherwise, he feels he will have to move out.",prompt1:"What would you say to Stan and your other housemates?",prompt2:"What is your approach to working with someone whose beliefs are vastly different from your own?"},
{category:"Ethics",scenario:"You are an employee paired with Ryan at a financial consulting firm. Your boss asks you both to complete a major industry report by Monday morning. After she leaves, Ryan says: \"I'm totally wiped. I was going to get my guy to drop off some Adderall to get us through the weekend. It really helps me get things done faster. Do you want a couple?\"",prompt1:"How would you respond to Ryan's question?",prompt2:"Do you think universities should be more proactive in preventing widespread Adderall misuse among their students?"},
{category:"Ethics",scenario:"You are in a study group. A friend obtained last year's exam from a teaching assistant and forwarded it to everyone. Immediately after, Marcine — another member — emails you privately to say she will report the breach to the professor with everyone's names, and asks you not to warn the others so they can't 'hide the evidence.'",prompt1:"Do you think Marcine's approach is fair? Why or why not?",prompt2:"What would you do?"},
{category:"Conflict Resolution",scenario:"In your study group, John is upset that Marshal's workload was redistributed after Marshal was hospitalised. A photo has since appeared on Marshal's Facebook showing him at a pool party. The group's work, if submitted, would give Marshal the same grade despite not contributing. Steve turns to you and asks how to proceed.",prompt1:"What do you recommend to your group members?",prompt2:"Do you think it is okay to report a concern to a supervisor based on a suspicion? Why or why not?"},
{category:"Personal",scenario:"You are captain of your high school basketball team preparing for regional championships next week. Your mother calls in distress — her sister has died unexpectedly. Your aunt was not close to the family and you barely know her. The funeral is the same day as your championships, four hours away by car, and you don't have a driver's licence.",prompt1:"Do you attend the funeral or the game? Why?",prompt2:"Describe a time when you had to make a similarly challenging decision."},
{category:"Ethics",scenario:"You are a nurse in a rural area. A GP has written you a prescription for antibiotics without examining you. In a pharmacy later that day, you see one of your patients — a 12-year-old boy named Ethan — waiting with what looks like the same prescription. Ethan's mother is not present. Ethan tells you the GP 'called it in' without seeing him either.",prompt1:"What would you do?",prompt2:"How do you balance the convenience of telehealth prescribing against the risks of not examining a patient in person — especially a child?"},
{category:"Conflict Resolution",scenario:"You are a resident physician. A nurse tells you that another resident, Dr. Kim, has been documenting vital signs without actually taking them — recording normal values to save time. No patient has been harmed yet, but the nurse is worried. She asks you not to use her name if you report it.",prompt1:"What do you do?",prompt2:"How do you balance loyalty to a colleague with your obligation to patient safety?"},
{category:"Ethics",scenario:"You are a student on a clinical placement. You notice that a senior surgeon consistently refers to female patients using dismissive language and appears to give them less time than male patients during rounds. Other staff seem uncomfortable but no one has said anything. One of the patients asks you why 'the doctor seemed annoyed with her.'",prompt1:"What do you do?",prompt2:"How do systemic biases in healthcare affect patient outcomes, and whose responsibility is it to address them?"},
{category:"Personal",scenario:"You are a university student. You have been selected for a prestigious internship overseas that begins in three months. Your younger brother has just been diagnosed with a serious mental illness and is struggling. Your parents are managing but are clearly overwhelmed. The internship is a once-in-a-decade opportunity.",prompt1:"What factors are you weighing, and what do you decide?",prompt2:"How do you think about your obligations to your family versus your obligations to yourself?"},
{category:"Conflict Resolution",scenario:"You work part-time at a café. Your manager has been scheduling you for shifts that conflict with your university timetable despite you giving her your availability weeks ago. When you raise it, she says the roster 'can't be changed now' and implies you should sort out your own shift swaps. Two colleagues have already said they can't swap.",prompt1:"What do you do?",prompt2:"When a workplace policy or decision directly conflicts with your personal obligations, how do you approach resolving it?"},
{category:"Ethics",scenario:"You are a university student working in a campus café. A regular customer — a postgraduate student named Niamh — comes in looking severely distressed. While making her order, she mentions that her supervisor has told her if she doesn't submit her thesis by Friday she will be expelled from the program. She says she hasn't slept in four days and has been relying on energy drinks. As she pays, you notice her hands are trembling badly and she mentions offhand that she's been having heart palpitations but 'can't afford to stop now.'",prompt1:"What do you do?",prompt2:"Niamh says: 'Please don't make this a bigger deal than it is — I just need my coffee.' How do you respond to this?"},
{category:"Ethics",scenario:"You are a student volunteer at a hospital. An elderly patient — Mr. Torres, 82 — asks you to help him leave the ward. He says he has not been told why he is being kept and just wants to go home. He seems lucid and is not distressed. You know that his ward has a 'do not discharge without physician approval' note on the file, but no one is available to ask right now.",prompt1:"What do you do?",prompt2:"How do you think about patient autonomy when someone wants to make a decision that may not be in their best medical interest?"},
{category:"Conflict Resolution",scenario:"You are a resident in a shared apartment block. Your downstairs neighbour — a single mother of two young children — has knocked on your door asking if you could please stop using your treadmill before 7am, as the noise wakes her babies. You have been using the treadmill at 6am because it is the only time you have before work. She looks exhausted and apologises for bothering you. You have a medical condition that makes evening exercise difficult.",prompt1:"How would you respond to her in this moment?",prompt2:"What is a fair way to resolve a conflict where both parties have genuine and reasonable needs?"},
{category:"Personal",scenario:"You are a final-year student who has just received a job offer from a prestigious company — the role you have worked toward for three years. The same week, your closest friend is diagnosed with a serious illness that will require a year of treatment. He doesn't ask you to change your plans, but you can see he is frightened and that his support network is thin. The job starts in three weeks.",prompt1:"What is going through your mind?",prompt2:"Give an example of a time in your life when you faced a genuine conflict between your own goals and the needs of someone close to you. What did you choose, and do you stand by it now?"},
{category:"Communication",scenario:"You are a team leader at a community youth centre. One of your volunteers — a 19-year-old named Bea — has been working with at-risk teenagers for six months. She is energetic and the kids clearly like her. However, in the last few weeks you have noticed she has been sharing personal details of her own difficult past with the teenagers during sessions — including details about past drug use — in an attempt to build rapport. Two other staff have raised concerns with you privately.",prompt1:"How do you approach this conversation with Bea?",prompt2:"What is the line between appropriate self-disclosure and oversharing in a professional helping role — and who is harmed when that line is crossed?"},
{category:"Ethics",scenario:"You are a close friend. Your friend Daniel has been battling severe depression for the past year and has been isolating himself from most people. He has recently confided in you — and only you — that he has been secretly researching assisted dying options, not because he has a terminal illness, but because he feels his quality of life is unbearable. He hasn't said he is going to act on anything, and he was very clear that he only told you because he trusted you completely and does not want you to involve anyone else. You are genuinely worried.",prompt1:"What is going through your mind, and what do you say to Daniel in this moment?",prompt2:"Daniel asks you directly: 'You're not going to tell anyone, are you?' How do you respond?"},
{category:"Conflict Resolution",scenario:"You are a third-year university student and the president of your faculty's student society. Two of your most capable committee members — Sophie and Marcus — have had a serious falling out after a disagreement at a social event last month. They are now refusing to work together, which is causing real problems as they co-lead your biggest event of the year. Other committee members are starting to take sides. The event is six weeks away and cannot be delayed.",prompt1:"How would you approach Sophie and Marcus individually, and what would you say?",prompt2:"Some committee members are suggesting you simply remove one of them from the event to resolve the tension quickly. What are your thoughts on this approach?"},
{category:"Personal",scenario:"You are a university student in your final semester. Your father, who immigrated to this country and worked two jobs for twenty years specifically so you could get a degree, has been diagnosed with an aggressive form of cancer. He has been given 6–12 months. He tells you not to worry about him and insists you focus on finishing your degree. Your mother, however, calls you crying every second night, saying she cannot manage alone and needs you to come home. Your home is a 5-hour drive away.",prompt1:"What is going through your mind, and what do you do?",prompt2:"Your father finds out your mother has been calling you and apologises, saying: 'She shouldn't have done that — this is not your burden.' How does this change, if at all, how you think about the situation?"},
{category:"Ethics",scenario:"You are a retail employee. You are working alone on a quiet weekday. An elderly woman comes in and begins carefully selecting items. You notice she is placing several low-value items into her bag without scanning them. She pays for a few things at the register and leaves. You are fairly certain this was intentional, but not completely sure.",prompt1:"What do you do in this moment?",prompt2:"How would your approach change if this were a teenager in school uniform, or a young mother with a child?"},
{category:"Conflict Resolution",scenario:"You are a volunteer at a community legal centre. A man in his 50s comes in asking for help with a tenancy dispute. As you begin to take his details, it becomes clear he is highly distressed and keeps veering off the practical issue — talking about his ex-wife, his estrangement from his children, and feeling like 'everything is falling apart.' He hasn't asked for emotional support. He came for legal help. Your supervisor is waiting for you to complete his intake form.",prompt1:"How do you handle this conversation?",prompt2:"What does this moment ask of you beyond your formal role — and how do you offer that without overstepping or making assumptions about what he needs?"},
{category:"Ethics",scenario:"You are a university student. During an exam, you notice the person sitting next to you — someone you don't know — clearly reading from a folded piece of paper hidden in their sleeve. The exam is worth 40% of the grade and is graded on a curve, meaning their score directly affects yours. You are three rows from the invigilator and the exam ends in fifteen minutes.",prompt1:"What do you do in this moment, and what are the considerations pulling you in different directions?",prompt2:"The exam ends before you can do anything. What, if anything, do you do now?"},
{category:"Ethics",scenario:"You are a friend. A close friend Lena, whom you've known for six years, confides that she has been accepting money from her grandmother under false pretences — telling her grandmother the money is for university fees when in fact she has been spending it on rent and personal expenses. Her grandmother is in her 80s, lives alone, and has a modest fixed income. Lena does not seem troubled by this. She tells you she's 'not hurting anyone.'",prompt1:"What do you say to Lena in this conversation?",prompt2:"How do you think Lena has arrived at the belief that this isn't hurting anyone — and what does that tell you about how people justify actions they know are wrong?"},
{category:"Ethics",scenario:"You are a convenience store employee working a late shift alone. A man in his 40s comes in looking distressed and asks you if you have a first aid kit. He says his young daughter cut her hand badly in the carpark. You can see blood on his shirt. Your manager has a strict policy: employees must not leave the register unattended, and all medical situations must be referred to emergency services only.",prompt1:"What do you do right now?",prompt2:"When following policy would lead to an outcome that feels clearly wrong, how do you decide when to act against it — and who carries the responsibility for that decision?"},
{category:"Conflict Resolution",scenario:"You are a senior student in a small honours cohort of eight. One student, Marcus, has been dominating every group discussion — not maliciously, but with an intensity that leaves others visibly reluctant to contribute. Two other students have separately told you they've stopped trying to share ideas because they feel 'talked over.' The supervisor has not noticed. There are no formal mechanisms for raising this, and Marcus is a close friend of yours.",prompt1:"How do you approach this situation?",prompt2:"Describe a time when you had to address a friend's behaviour that was affecting others, even though they had no idea. What did you say, and how did they respond?"},
{category:"Conflict Resolution",scenario:"You are a team member on a community charity project. Your group has been fundraising for six months toward a specific cause. Two weeks before the final event, the project leader — without consulting the group — announces she has redirected a portion of the funds toward a different charity that she personally prefers, citing 'strategic realignment.' The original donors have not been told. Half the group privately agrees with your discomfort; the other half supports the leader's decision and says 'the outcome is still good.'",prompt1:"How do you respond to the leader, and what do you think needs to happen now?",prompt2:"Is 'the outcome is still good' a sufficient justification for changing how donated funds are used without transparency — and where does that reasoning lead if applied broadly?"},
{category:"Conflict Resolution",scenario:"You are a postgraduate student sharing an office with four others. One office-mate, Jin, has been playing lo-fi music quietly through a speaker for weeks. Most people haven't minded, but one student — Amara — has asked him twice to stop, saying it breaks her concentration. Jin has been politely apologetic each time but continues within a day or two. Amara has now come to you, clearly frustrated, and asks you to back her up when she raises it again as a group.",prompt1:"What do you say to Amara, and how do you approach the situation when the group is next together?",prompt2:"What is the difference between supporting a colleague and taking sides — and how do you navigate that distinction when both people have reasonable positions?"},
{category:"Personal",scenario:"You are a volunteer coordinator for a charity that provides meals to homeless individuals. One of your most dedicated volunteers, a retired man named George who has been coming every Saturday for three years, has recently been making comments that some of the recipients find patronising and occasionally offensive. Two recipients have separately mentioned it to you. George is unaware and clearly means no harm.",prompt1:"How do you approach this with George?",prompt2:"Describe a time when you had to give critical feedback to someone who was well-intentioned but causing harm without realising it. What made that conversation difficult, and how did you handle it?"},
{category:"Ethics",scenario:"You are a university student. Your housemate asks you to be the designated driver for a group night out. Late in the evening, you discover your housemate — who organised the whole night — has been secretly drinking despite telling everyone he was also staying sober so 'the numbers worked.' He is now asking you to drive a group of seven people home in a car that seats five, saying: 'No one will notice and it's just around the corner.'",prompt1:"What do you do?",prompt2:"How does the fact that your housemate deceived you about staying sober affect how you approach this situation?"},
{category:"Professionalism",scenario:"You are a student representative on your university's academic integrity committee. A case is brought before the committee involving a student caught submitting an AI-generated essay. The student is a single parent who explains that she had a family emergency the week the essay was due, didn't ask for an extension because she 'didn't want to seem like she was making excuses,' and used AI in desperation. This is her first academic integrity violation.",prompt1:"How should the committee approach this case?",prompt2:"Do you think universities have kept pace with the ethical questions raised by AI-generated work? What policies would you recommend?"},
{category:"Conflict Resolution",scenario:"You are a shift supervisor at a retail store. Two of your employees — both of whom you consider good workers — have had a falling out over a scheduling dispute. One of them, Maya, has started leaving tasks incomplete that she knows the other, Sean, will have to finish. Sean has come to you saying he feels targeted and the situation is affecting his mental health. Maya denies it is intentional.",prompt1:"How do you handle this situation?",prompt2:"What does fairness look like when one party denies behaviour that the other person experiences as clearly intentional?"},
{category:"Personal",scenario:"You are a second-year university student. A professor whose class you are enrolled in has given you a grade that you believe is unfair and that could significantly affect your academic record.",prompt1:"What do you do?",prompt2:"Describe a time when you had to advocate for yourself in a situation where you had significantly less power than the other person. What did you do, and how did it turn out?"},
{category:"Communication",scenario:"An elderly man — a 78-year-old Korean-Australian — has been referred to you after his neighbour reported concerns about his wellbeing. He arrived on time but is now sitting quietly, answering every question with 'I am fine' and offering polite, brief replies. His body language tells a different story. You have 30 minutes with him.",prompt1:"How do you approach this conversation?",prompt2:"What do you think is happening for this man beneath the surface — and what would genuine connection look like in this context?"},
{category:"Communication",scenario:"You are a first-year intern at a company. Your team lead asks you to run a short training session for five colleagues on a new internal software platform. Halfway through, it becomes obvious the group is far more advanced than you assumed — two of them have already used the platform and are visibly frustrated. One makes a comment under their breath about it being a 'waste of time.'",prompt1:"What do you do right now, in this moment?",prompt2:"What does this experience teach you about the assumptions we make when preparing to communicate with an audience — and how do you recover gracefully when those assumptions are wrong?"},
{category:"Ethics",scenario:"You are a long-time employee at a small family-run business. The owner — a woman in her 60s who built the company from nothing and whom you genuinely respect — has been making decisions lately that seem increasingly erratic. She has double-booked major clients, forgotten conversations that happened recently, and become uncharacteristically emotional. You suspect she may be experiencing early cognitive decline. She has no family involved in the business, and you are her most trusted employee.",prompt1:"What is your responsibility here, if any, and what do you do?",prompt2:"How do you think your employer would feel if she knew you were having these concerns about her — and how does that shape your approach?"},
{category:"Communication",scenario:"You are a volunteer visitor at a residential aged care facility. You regularly visit an 84-year-old resident named Arthur, who has no family and few visitors. During today's visit, Arthur becomes emotional and tells you that he overheard two staff members last week laughing about how he 'probably won't last the winter.' He is not visibly unwell. He says he hasn't slept since hearing it and asks you: 'Do you think they're right?'",prompt1:"What do you say to Arthur in this moment?",prompt2:"How do you think Arthur has been experiencing the time since he overheard those comments, and what does that tell you about the impact of careless words in care settings?"},
{category:"Professionalism",scenario:"You are a second-year student on a group project. Your group's final presentation is tomorrow. Tonight, reviewing the shared document, you discover that your group's highest-achieving member — who everyone relies on and who volunteered to compile the final version — has inserted three paragraphs that were clearly taken directly from an online source, unreferenced and unacknowledged. The rest of your contributions are entirely original. If submitted as-is, the entire group will have a plagiarism violation on their record.",prompt1:"What do you do tonight?",prompt2:"If your group member insists the paragraphs were 'just a placeholder that they forgot to rewrite,' how do you assess that explanation, and does it change anything?"},
{category:"Personal",scenario:"You are a postgraduate student. A close friend and fellow student, someone you have known for five years, is applying for the same highly competitive scholarship as you. You both need this scholarship — it would fund two years of your research. The committee has informally told you that you are the front-runner. Your friend asks if you would be willing to review his application and give honest feedback, the way you always have for each other. His application, as it stands, is weak in two specific ways that you can clearly see.",prompt1:"What do you do?",prompt2:"Describe a time when your loyalty to a friend and your own self-interest genuinely pulled against each other. How did you decide what to do, and how did it turn out?"},
{category:"Ethics",scenario:"You are a second-year university student. A member of your group project team — someone you don't know well — has listed significantly more contributions than they actually made on the group's self-assessment form. Their listed contributions overlap with yours in a way that, if accepted, would suggest your individual contribution was smaller than it was. The form is due tonight. You became aware of this by accident.",prompt1:"What do you do?",prompt2:"What are the downstream harms when people misrepresent collaborative work — and what makes it particularly hard to address?"},
{category:"Professionalism",scenario:"You are an intern at a reputable firm. Your supervisor is brilliant and has been a strong advocate for you — but in group settings, you've noticed she consistently interrupts and speaks over the more junior women in the team in a way she doesn't do with the men. The pattern is subtle enough that you think she might not be aware of it. You are the most junior person in the room when it happens. No one else has said anything.",prompt1:"Do you say something — and if so, to whom and how?",prompt2:"Give an example of a time you noticed a pattern of behaviour — not a single incident — that you felt was wrong, but where speaking up felt risky or uncomfortable. What did you do, and what factors shaped that decision?"},
{category:"Professionalism",scenario:"You have just started a graduate position and are keen to make a good impression. A senior colleague you respect asks you to cover for them with a client — to say they are 'in a meeting' when in fact they've left early for a personal appointment. It's a small thing, they say, and the client won't notice. You can tell the request makes sense to them and they're not asking you to do anything they'd consider significant.",prompt1:"How do you respond to this colleague in the moment?",prompt2:"Give an example of a time early in a job, volunteer role, or team setting where you were asked — directly or indirectly — to compromise on something you valued. How did you respond, and what did that experience shape in you?"},
{category:"Communication",scenario:"You are a new team leader. You've just taken over a team of five from a previous manager who was very well-liked and had led the group for four years. In your first team meeting, you share some changes you'd like to make to how the group operates. One senior team member — quietly but clearly — says: 'That's not how we do things here.' The room goes silent.",prompt1:"What do you say in this moment?",prompt2:"How do you build credibility with a team that had a strong previous leader — and what mistakes do new leaders typically make in this situation?"},
{category:"Communication",scenario:"You are a health educator running a community workshop on childhood vaccination. A parent in the audience raises her hand and states firmly that her child had an adverse reaction after a vaccination and that she believes the 'mainstream narrative' is suppressing real data. Several other parents are nodding. You have fifteen minutes left in the session.",prompt1:"How do you handle this in the moment?",prompt2:"How do you hold space for someone's genuine fear and experience while still maintaining the integrity of evidence-based public health messaging?"},
{category:"Communication",scenario:"You are a student who has been working part-time as a customer service representative. A customer calls in, initially calm, to dispute a charge on their account. As you explain the company's policy, they become increasingly hostile — eventually shouting and using language that is personally offensive. Company protocol says you may end the call after two verbal warnings. You've issued one. The customer then suddenly stops and says, voice breaking: 'I'm sorry. I'm sorry. My wife just left me. I don't know why I'm doing this.'",prompt1:"What do you do in this moment?",prompt2:"What does this shift in the customer's behaviour ask of you — and how do you hold both your professional role and your human response at the same time?"}
];


// ══ MMI STATIONS — generated by Key2MD prompt generator ══
// Role-Play stations removed. All stations have prompt1–4.
// prompt3 and prompt4 activate for 3–4 prompt presets (Extended, Quickfire, Random Probe).
const MMI_STATIONS=[
{category:"Motivation",scenario:"You are sitting in an MMI at a leading Australian medical school. The examiner looks up from their notes and says: 'Tell me why you want to study medicine. And please — avoid the clichés.'",prompt1:"Why do you want to study medicine?",prompt2:"What has your path to this interview taught you about yourself?",prompt3:"You've given me your reasons for wanting to study medicine — now convince me why medicine needs you specifically. What unique perspective or capability do you bring that other candidates don't?",prompt4:"Imagine you're 10 years into your medical career and you're having doubts about whether you made the right choice. What would you tell your younger self sitting here today, and what would you need to hear to recommit?"},
{category:"Ethics",scenario:"You are a medical student on placement. You observe your supervising consultant dismiss a patient's concerns about a proposed treatment with visible impatience, saying 'Trust me, I've done this a thousand times.' The patient looks uncertain but says nothing more. The treatment plan proceeds.",prompt1:"What are your thoughts on what just happened?",prompt2:"What, if anything, would you do — and how do you weigh speaking up against the risk of undermining a senior colleague?",prompt3:"You've identified concerns about informed consent and patient autonomy, but some would argue that excessive explanation can actually harm patients by creating unnecessary anxiety about procedures with minimal risk. How do you respond to this view?",prompt4:"Imagine this exact scenario happens again next week with a different patient. Walk me through your specific actions in the first two minutes after witnessing it."},
{category:"Conflict Resolution",scenario:"You are a third-year medical student on a clinical team. A nurse pulls you aside and tells you that she believes the registrar made an error in a patient's medication order. She is hesitant to raise it herself and asks you to 'look into it.' The registrar is known for being dismissive when challenged.",prompt1:"What do you do?",prompt2:"What does this situation reveal about the role of hierarchy in patient safety, and how should healthcare teams manage it?",prompt3:"You've identified a clear process for handling this situation, but what if the nurse later tells you she's experienced retaliation from this registrar before when raising concerns? How does this change your approach, and what are you willing to risk as a student?",prompt4:"Imagine you're now the registrar in five years, and a student approaches you about a potential medication error you've made. How would you want them to handle it, and what does this tell you about the kind of senior clinician you want to become?"},
{category:"Policy",scenario:"A government body is considering a policy that would require all medical students to complete a mandatory rural placement of at least 12 months before graduating, in response to the critical shortage of doctors in regional Australia.",prompt1:"What do you see as the strongest arguments for and against this policy?",prompt2:"How do you think medical schools should balance producing specialists for cities versus generalists for rural communities?",prompt3:"If you were forced to choose between this policy or a 50% reduction in medical school places nationwide, which would you pick and why?",prompt4:"Looking at your own career aspirations, how would this mandatory rural placement actually change your specialty choices and timeline - be specific about the trade-offs you'd personally face."},
{category:"Motivation",scenario:"The examiner says: 'You've listed significant volunteer work in your application. I want to understand it more deeply. What did you actually learn from it — not what you were supposed to learn, but what genuinely surprised you or changed the way you think?'",prompt1:"What did your volunteer experience genuinely teach you?",prompt2:"How has it shaped what kind of doctor you want to be?",prompt3:"You say volunteering changed how you think about medicine, but I'm skeptical — most students say exactly that. Give me one specific moment where you genuinely questioned something you believed before, not just felt good about helping.",prompt4:"Now flip this around — what did you observe about the healthcare system or patient care during your volunteering that actually worried you or made you uncomfortable?"},
{category:"Ethics",scenario:"A patient in her mid-30s is admitted following a suicide attempt. She is medically stable and coherent. She tells you clearly that she does not want her family notified, and she does not want any psychiatric intervention. 'I know my own mind,' she says. 'I just want to go home.'",prompt1:"What are the ethical tensions in this situation?",prompt2:"How do you balance a patient's right to autonomy with a duty of care — and is there ever a point where that balance tips decisively one way?",prompt3:"You've decided to respect her autonomy and discharge her, but as you're completing the paperwork, her sister calls the ward saying the family is 'deeply concerned' and threatens to sue if anything happens. What do you do right now?",prompt4:"Think about a time when someone dismissed your concerns about your own wellbeing or mental state. How does that experience inform how you'd approach this patient's refusal of help?"},
{category:"Conflict Resolution",scenario:"You are a member of a student research group. Over several months, you notice that one member consistently takes more credit than is due in group presentations, while another quieter member whose contributions are substantial is consistently uncredited. Neither has raised it.",prompt1:"What do you do?",prompt2:"Why do you think the uncredited member hasn't raised it themselves — and what does that tell you about the dynamics at play?",prompt3:"You've decided to address this, but the credit-taking member responds by saying 'I do most of the work anyway, and [quiet member] never speaks up, so they obviously don't mind.' How do you handle this pushback?",prompt4:"Imagine you're now the research supervisor who becomes aware of this pattern across multiple student groups. What systemic changes would you implement to prevent this dynamic from occurring?"},
{category:"Policy",scenario:"There is an ongoing debate about whether medical school interviews — including the MMI format — are effective at selecting the best future doctors. Some researchers argue they favour candidates who are coached, articulate, and socioculturally advantaged.",prompt1:"What is your view on whether the MMI is an effective selection tool?",prompt2:"If you were designing a fairer admissions process, what would it look like?",prompt3:"Given that you're here doing an MMI right now, how do you reconcile participating in a system you might have just criticized?",prompt4:"A rural student with excellent grades but no interview coaching gets rejected while a city student with slightly lower marks but professional preparation gets in. What specifically would you tell the rural student about fairness in medicine?"},
{category:"Motivation",scenario:"The examiner says: 'A lot of applicants tell me they want to be a doctor because they want to make a difference. But doctors who burn out also wanted to make a difference. What makes you think you'll last?'",prompt1:"What do you think will sustain you through the hardest parts of a medical career?",prompt2:"Describe a time in your life when you were under sustained pressure — not a single crisis, but a prolonged period of difficulty. How did you actually cope, and what does that tell you about your resilience?",prompt3:"You've talked about what will sustain you, but let's be honest — every burnt-out doctor once believed they had those same qualities. What specific warning signs would tell you that you're heading toward burnout, and what would you actually do differently than those who didn't make it?",prompt4:"Think about the healthcare workers you've observed or worked with — what did you notice about the ones who seemed energised versus exhausted? How do you plan to cultivate those energising factors in your own practice?"},
{category:"Motivation",scenario:"The examiner says: 'Tell me about a time you encountered suffering — not in a clinical setting, just in life — and what it asked of you.'",prompt1:"Describe the experience and how you responded.",prompt2:"Looking back, is there anything you wish you had done differently — and what does that reflection tell you about the kind of practitioner you want to become?",prompt3:"You've told me what you learned about yourself, but what did that experience teach you about the person who was suffering — and how will that shape how you listen to patients who are in pain?",prompt4:"Think about your response in that moment — walk me through your actual thought process as it was happening, not the neat story you've constructed afterwards."},
{category:"Motivation",scenario:"The examiner asks: 'Medicine will ask you to see people at their most vulnerable every single day. What in your background has actually prepared you for that — not in theory, but in practice?'",prompt1:"What experiences have genuinely prepared you for sustained exposure to human suffering and vulnerability?",prompt2:"Describe a specific moment when someone was at their most vulnerable in front of you — not a clinical moment, just a human one — and tell me what you did, and what it asked of you emotionally.",prompt3:"You've told me about handling vulnerability in others, but medicine will also expose your own vulnerabilities — your mistakes, your limitations, your emotional breaking points. What makes you think you can handle being that exposed yourself?",prompt4:"Take that specific vulnerable moment you described and imagine you had to witness fifty similar situations in a single week, then go home to your family and be present for them. Walk me through how you'd actually manage that transition."},
{category:"Motivation",scenario:"The examiner says: 'I want you to tell me about a failure — something you genuinely got wrong, where you bore real responsibility. Not a disguised success story.'",prompt1:"What was the failure, and what was your role in it?",prompt2:"What changed in how you behave as a result — and how would you know if it had actually changed, versus just telling yourself it had?",prompt3:"Walk me through your thinking process during that failure — what were you telling yourself at the time that prevented you from seeing what was actually happening?",prompt4:"If a close friend made the exact same mistake you did, what would you tell them, and would that advice be different from what you tell yourself?"},
{category:"Motivation",scenario:"The examiner says: 'I want to understand your relationship with uncertainty. Medicine is full of situations where you won't know the answer, where the evidence is unclear, where reasonable people disagree. How do you actually handle not knowing?'",prompt1:"How do you personally relate to uncertainty — intellectually and emotionally?",prompt2:"Give me a specific example of a time you had to act or make a decision under genuine uncertainty — where the right answer wasn't clear and the stakes were real. What did you do, and what did it teach you?",prompt3:"You've described how you handle uncertainty, but let's be honest — most medical students I interview say they're 'comfortable with uncertainty' yet struggle when they actually face it. What makes you think you'll be different when a patient is deteriorating and you genuinely don't know what's wrong?",prompt4:"Think about the healthcare system more broadly — how should we train doctors to make decisions when evidence is limited or conflicting, and how do we balance admitting uncertainty with maintaining patient confidence?"},
{category:"Motivation",scenario:"The examiner asks: 'Tell me about someone — not a famous doctor, not a textbook figure — a real person in your life who has shaped how you think about medicine or healthcare.'",prompt1:"Who is this person, and what specifically have they shown you?",prompt2:"How has knowing them changed what you think a good doctor actually looks like?",prompt3:"Think about a moment when this person's approach to health or illness directly conflicted with what you'd learned from textbooks or formal education. How did you reconcile that tension?",prompt4:"If you had to teach a first-year medical student the most important lesson this person taught you, but you only had two minutes and couldn't mention their name or story, what would you say?"},
{category:"Motivation",scenario:"The examiner says: 'You're applying to one of the most competitive programs in the country. Strip away the status, the difficulty, the prestige. Why this, really?'",prompt1:"What is your honest, unguarded answer for why you want to be a doctor?",prompt2:"What would it mean to you personally — not professionally — to become one?",prompt3:"Tell me about a moment when you seriously considered not pursuing medicine — what pulled you back?",prompt4:"If you had to convince a burnt-out doctor why this career is still worth it, what would you say?"},
{category:"Ethics",scenario:"You are a final-year medical student on placement. You discover that a fellow student — someone you consider a friend — has been systematically exaggerating their clinical log entries, claiming procedures they observed but did not perform. They are due to graduate next month. No patient has been harmed.",prompt1:"What do you do?",prompt2:"Your friend says: 'These logs are just a bureaucratic box-tick — no one even reads them. You're going to ruin my career over nothing.' How do you respond?",prompt3:"You've decided to report your friend, but now you're sitting across from the academic coordinator who asks: 'Are you absolutely certain about these allegations, and are you prepared for the consequences this will have on your relationship and your friend's future?' What do you say?",prompt4:"A year later, you're now a junior doctor and you notice a colleague consistently documenting procedures they didn't actually perform in patient notes. How does your experience with your medical school friend influence your approach to this new situation?"},
{category:"Ethics",scenario:"You are a junior doctor. A patient — a 55-year-old man recovering from a cardiac procedure — asks you directly: 'My wife has been asking the nurses about my condition. I'd like you to make sure no one tells her anything.' You have already spoken briefly with the wife, who is clearly anxious and involved in his care.",prompt1:"How do you respond to the patient in this moment?",prompt2:"What does this situation reveal about the tension between patient confidentiality and family-centred care?",prompt3:"The wife approaches you later that day, visibly distressed, saying 'I know something's wrong - he won't talk to me and the nurses won't either. I'm his wife of 30 years, don't I have a right to know?' How do you handle this conversation?",prompt4:"Think about your own family relationships - would you want medical information withheld from someone close to you, and how does that personal perspective influence your professional obligations here?"},
{category:"Ethics",scenario:"You are a GP. A patient you have known for five years — a 40-year-old truck driver — presents with a new diagnosis of epilepsy. He is on a treatment plan and his seizures are not yet controlled. He tells you he has not informed his employer and does not intend to, because he will lose his job. He is the primary income earner for his family.",prompt1:"What are your obligations in this situation?",prompt2:"How do you weigh a patient's privacy and livelihood against potential risk to others?",prompt3:"Your patient becomes angry when you explain the legal requirements, saying 'You doctors don't understand what it's like to support a family — if I lose this job, we lose everything.' How do you respond to his accusation that you're prioritizing bureaucracy over his family's survival?",prompt4:"Six months later, this patient has a seizure while driving and causes a multi-car accident with serious injuries. What systems or safeguards could have prevented this outcome, and what does this tell us about how medicine should handle these competing interests?"},
{category:"Ethics",scenario:"You are on a hospital ethics committee. A case is brought to you: a 16-year-old patient with a chronic illness has refused a procedure her parents and medical team believe is necessary. She is assessed as having capacity. Her parents are demanding the procedure go ahead.",prompt1:"What is your view on this situation?",prompt2:"At what point — if ever — does a minor's right to refuse treatment override parental and medical authority?",prompt3:"The 16-year-old tells you privately that she's refusing because she doesn't want to burden her family with more medical costs and time off work. Does this change your position on respecting her autonomy?",prompt4:"You're now the parent in this scenario - your child is making what you believe is a life-threatening decision. Walk me through how you'd want the ethics committee to handle your case."},
{category:"Ethics",scenario:"You are a GP and a long-term patient comes in distressed. During the consultation he discloses, in confidence, that he has been physically abusive toward his partner. He has not been charged. His partner is not your patient.",prompt1:"What do you do with this information?",prompt2:"How do you hold the therapeutic relationship with this patient while also taking seriously your obligations to someone you have never met?",prompt3:"Your patient says he's ready to change and asks you to help him find anger management resources, but also begs you not to involve authorities because 'it will destroy everything.' How do you respond to his request for help while navigating your duty of care?",prompt4:"Three months later, this same patient's partner books an appointment with you as a new patient and during her consultation, you notice bruising consistent with domestic violence. What ethical considerations guide your approach now?"},
{category:"Ethics",scenario:"You are a registrar. A senior consultant asks you to document a clinical decision in a way that you believe misrepresents what actually happened. The consultant says: 'It's cleaner this way. No one gets hurt.' There is no immediate patient harm.",prompt1:"What do you do?",prompt2:"What does this situation reveal about the relationship between documentation, honesty, and accountability in medicine?",prompt3:"Think about a time you've been asked to bend the truth in a 'harmless' way - how is this medical situation similar or different to that experience?",prompt4:"If this becomes standard practice in your department, what happens to medical culture over the next decade?"},
{category:"Ethics",scenario:"A terminally ill patient, fully lucid, asks you to help her die. You are in a jurisdiction where voluntary assisted dying is legal and she meets the criteria. However, it is against your personal beliefs.",prompt1:"How do you navigate this?",prompt2:"Is conscientious objection ever an acceptable response in medicine — and if so, where are its limits?",prompt3:"You've decided to refer her to another doctor who will help her die, but she says 'I trust you, not some stranger — please don't abandon me now.' How do you respond to her plea?",prompt4:"Imagine you're this patient's daughter watching your mother suffer while her doctor wrestles with personal beliefs. What would you want that doctor to prioritize?"},
{category:"Ethics",scenario:"You are a junior doctor and you make a medication error that, fortunately, does not harm the patient. You correct it before anyone else notices. You are now wondering whether to disclose it.",prompt1:"What do you do?",prompt2:"What does a culture of disclosure actually require from individual practitioners — and what does it require from institutions?",prompt3:"Think about a time when you made a mistake that nobody else knew about — how did you decide whether to tell someone, and what does that reveal about your character as a future doctor?",prompt4:"If reporting this error would trigger a formal investigation that could delay your career progression by months, does your answer change?"},
{category:"Ethics",scenario:"A 14-year-old presents to your GP clinic asking for contraception. She does not want her parents told. She appears mature and understands what she is asking for.",prompt1:"What do you do?",prompt2:"How does the concept of Gillick competence change the way you think about adolescent patients — and what are its limits?",prompt3:"You've established she's Gillick competent, but three months later she's pregnant and wants a termination — still without parental involvement. Walk me through how your approach changes when the stakes escalate from contraception to abortion.",prompt4:"Now imagine you're the parent who discovers their 14-year-old has been accessing reproductive health services without your knowledge. How do you balance respecting your child's autonomy with your parental responsibilities?"},
{category:"Conflict Resolution",scenario:"You are a junior doctor on a busy surgical ward. The ward clerk — a long-standing staff member who is well-liked — has been consistently prioritising certain patients' discharge paperwork over others in a way that delays discharges for patients from a particular cultural background. You are not certain this is intentional.",prompt1:"How do you approach this situation?",prompt2:"How do you address a pattern of behaviour that may or may not be deliberate — when raising it risks labelling someone unfairly, but not raising it risks harm continuing?",prompt3:"A senior nurse tells you she's noticed the same pattern but warns that the ward clerk has powerful allies in administration who could make your life difficult if you push this. What do you do now?",prompt4:"Think about a time when you might have unconsciously treated people differently based on assumptions. How does that experience inform your approach here?"},
{category:"Conflict Resolution",scenario:"Your study group of five is preparing for finals. One member has suggested you all pool and share answers to past exam questions. The document is now also including specific questions that he says he 'heard were definitely on the paper from someone who did it last year.' Two members are enthusiastic. Two are uncomfortable. Everyone is looking at you.",prompt1:"What do you do?",prompt2:"How do group dynamics make it harder to act on your values in these situations — and what does it take to hold your position when the group is moving in a different direction?",prompt3:"You decide to speak up against using the leaked questions, but the two enthusiastic members accuse you of being self-righteous and say you're jeopardizing everyone's chances when 'everyone else is probably doing this too.' How do you respond to their pushback?",prompt4:"Imagine you're now the Dean reviewing this situation after it's been reported - what factors would you weigh in deciding consequences, and how would you balance individual accountability versus the systemic pressures students face?"},
{category:"Conflict Resolution",scenario:"You are a resident. Your registrar, whom you respect and have a good relationship with, gives you feedback after a ward round that you felt was inaccurate and publicly delivered in a way that was humiliating. Other team members were present. You are still processing it.",prompt1:"How do you handle this?",prompt2:"What is the difference between feedback that is hard to hear and feedback that is genuinely unfair — and how do you respond to each?",prompt3:"You decide to approach your registrar privately about this feedback. They respond defensively, saying you're being oversensitive and that this is just how medicine works. How do you proceed?",prompt4:"Think about a time when you gave someone feedback that didn't land well. What would you want that person to do, and how does that inform your approach here?"},
{category:"Conflict Resolution",scenario:"You are part of a multidisciplinary team managing an elderly patient's care. The patient's son — who has medical power of attorney — is insisting on continuing aggressive treatment. The medical team, the palliative care team, and the nursing staff all believe further intervention is futile and causing suffering. The patient has not been able to express her wishes for some time.",prompt1:"How should this be managed?",prompt2:"What is the ethical and human weight of a medical power of attorney — and what happens when the person holding it is making decisions the team believes are not in the patient's interests?",prompt3:"You've outlined your approach, but now the son reveals he's a doctor himself and accuses your team of giving up too early because his mother is elderly. How do you respond to his expertise challenge while maintaining your position?",prompt4:"Step back from being the healthcare provider — imagine you're the patient's daughter watching this unfold between your brother and the medical team. What would you want to happen?"},
{category:"Conflict Resolution",scenario:"You are a GP. Two of your long-term patients are a married couple. You have been seeing them separately for years. The husband comes to you and discloses that he has had an affair and has a sexually transmitted infection. He begs you not to tell his wife, who is also your patient.",prompt1:"What do you do?",prompt2:"How do you manage ongoing care of both patients in a way that is ethical, when your knowledge of one affects your obligations to the other?",prompt3:"The husband threatens to change doctors and take his wife with him if you breach his confidentiality, potentially leaving them both without proper medical care. Does this change your approach?",prompt4:"Three months later, the wife comes in asking why you keep suggesting STI screening when she's been monogamous - how do you handle this conversation without lying?"},
{category:"Conflict Resolution",scenario:"You are a medical student on placement. You witness a nurse administer what you believe to be the wrong dose of a medication to a patient. You are not certain — you could have misread the chart. The nurse has 20 years of experience and you have been on the ward for two weeks.",prompt1:"What do you do in this moment?",prompt2:"How does your level of certainty affect your obligation to act — and what is the cost of getting this wrong in either direction?",prompt3:"The nurse later pulls you aside and says 'I've been doing this for two decades, and students like you questioning me undermines patient trust in the whole team.' How do you respond?",prompt4:"Imagine you're now the experienced nurse in this scenario, and a medical student approaches you with concerns about your medication administration. What would you want them to say and do?"},
{category:"Conflict Resolution",scenario:"You are a junior doctor. A colleague — a registrar you work closely with — has been coming in smelling of alcohol on morning shifts. No patient has been harmed. When you raise it privately, he says he's going through a divorce and asks you to keep it between you.",prompt1:"What do you do?",prompt2:"What does a doctor's duty of care extend to — and does it include other members of the team?",prompt3:"Two weeks later, you notice the same colleague making a medication error that could have been serious. How does this change your approach, and what specific actions will you take in the next 24 hours?",prompt4:"Think about a time when someone trusted you with sensitive information that put you in a difficult position. How do the principles you used then apply here, and where might they differ?"},
{category:"Conflict Resolution",scenario:"You are a senior medical student. You have been assigned to present a case to the team. After your presentation, the consultant — in front of the whole team — tells you your assessment was 'exactly the kind of sloppy thinking that gets patients killed.' Your assessment was, in fact, correct.",prompt1:"How do you respond in that moment?",prompt2:"What does this experience reveal about the culture of medicine — and how do you preserve your sense of self in environments that use humiliation as a teaching tool?",prompt3:"Six months later, you're now the consultant and witness a colleague doing exactly what happened to you — publicly humiliating a correct student. What do you do, and how do you balance your duty to the student against potential career consequences of challenging a peer?",prompt4:"You mentioned preserving your sense of self — but what if staying true to yourself means you can't function in this system? At what point would you consider that medicine itself might not be worth the psychological cost?"},
{category:"Conflict Resolution",scenario:"You are a GP. A patient's family contacts you outside of normal channels, asking you to share the patient's medical information and to consider changing his treatment plan. The patient — a 70-year-old man — has capacity and has explicitly told you he does not want his family involved in his care.",prompt1:"How do you respond to the family?",prompt2:"What does this situation reveal about the tension between family-centred and patient-centred care — and who gets to decide?",prompt3:"The family argues they know what's 'really best' for their father and that his refusal to involve them proves he's not thinking clearly. How do you respond to this challenge to his capacity?",prompt4:"Imagine you're the 70-year-old patient who discovers his family contacted you behind his back. What would this mean for your trust in both your doctor and your family?"},
{category:"Policy",scenario:"There is a growing movement to introduce a sugar tax in Australia — a levy on sugary drinks — as a public health measure to reduce obesity and type 2 diabetes.",prompt1:"What are the arguments for and against a sugar tax as a public health intervention?",prompt2:"When is it appropriate for governments to use taxation to influence health behaviour — and where should the line be drawn?",prompt3:"You've likely supported some form of government intervention here — but what if I told you that sugar taxes disproportionately burden low-income families who spend a higher percentage of their income on food, essentially making healthy choices a privilege of the wealthy?",prompt4:"Walk me through exactly how you would design and implement a sugar tax policy in Australia — what specific products, what tax rate, and how would you measure success in the first year?"},
{category:"Policy",scenario:"A major Australian hospital is considering introducing a policy of mandatory drug and alcohol testing for all clinical staff before each shift. The policy has been proposed following two incidents involving impaired clinicians. Unions are strongly opposed.",prompt1:"What are the key considerations for and against this policy?",prompt2:"How do you balance patient safety with the rights and wellbeing of healthcare workers?",prompt3:"If you were the hospital's chief medical officer and the union threatened to strike over this policy, potentially leaving the hospital understaffed, what would you do?",prompt4:"How might similar mandatory testing policies affect other high-stakes professions like pilots or teachers, and what does this tell us about healthcare's unique responsibilities?"},
{category:"Policy",scenario:"Australia's Medicare system funds GP consultations at a rate that many argue is too low to sustain bulk billing, leading to out-of-pocket costs that are highest for the people who can least afford them.",prompt1:"What are the systemic causes of declining bulk billing, and what would a fair solution look like?",prompt2:"How do you think about equity in healthcare access — and whose responsibility is it to ensure it?",prompt3:"You've outlined what should happen, but if you were the Health Minister with a fixed budget and powerful lobbying from both the AMA and patient advocacy groups, what specific trade-offs would you actually make?",prompt4:"Think about your own family's healthcare decisions over the past few years — how has cost influenced where you've sought care, and what does that tell you about your position on this issue?"},
{category:"Policy",scenario:"There is an ongoing debate about whether voluntary assisted dying should be further expanded in Australia — including for people with treatment-resistant mental illness, not just terminal physical illness.",prompt1:"What are the strongest arguments on each side of this debate?",prompt2:"How do you hold a personal view on a deeply contested moral question while remaining able to practise ethically across a diverse patient population?",prompt3:"If you were designing the policy framework for this expansion, what specific safeguards would you implement to prevent coercion while respecting patient autonomy?",prompt4:"How might Indigenous Australian perspectives on mental health, healing, and end-of-life decisions challenge or enrich the predominantly Western biomedical framework driving this debate?"},
{category:"Policy",scenario:"Preventive medicine — stopping disease before it starts — is consistently underfunded compared to acute care in Australia.",prompt1:"Why is preventive medicine chronically underfunded, and what are the structural barriers to changing that?",prompt2:"If you were advising a health minister, what one policy change would you prioritise and why?",prompt3:"You've argued for more preventive funding, but critics say it's just politicians spending money on feel-good programs with no measurable short-term results that voters care about. How do you respond to that charge?",prompt4:"Think about your own healthcare choices over the past year — when did you prioritise prevention versus waiting for problems to emerge, and what drove those decisions?"},
{category:"Policy",scenario:"Australia has a significant and well-documented gap in health outcomes between Indigenous and non-Indigenous Australians. This gap has persisted despite decades of policy attention.",prompt1:"What are the root causes of the Indigenous health gap in Australia, and why have existing policies fallen short?",prompt2:"What do you think is actually required — structurally and culturally — to close it?",prompt3:"If you were Health Minister and had to choose just one intervention to fund for the next decade, what would it be and how would you measure whether it's actually working?",prompt4:"Indigenous health advocates argue that well-meaning non-Indigenous doctors often perpetuate the problem despite good intentions. How might your own background limit your effectiveness in this space?"},
{category:"Policy",scenario:"There is growing evidence that social determinants — housing, income, education, food security — account for more of the variation in health outcomes than access to healthcare itself.",prompt1:"What does this evidence suggest about how we should allocate health resources?",prompt2:"What is the appropriate role of doctors and health systems in addressing factors that lie outside their traditional domain?",prompt3:"If you were Australia's Health Minister and had to cut either hospital funding or social housing investment by 20%, which would you choose and why?",prompt4:"Some argue that doctors focusing on social issues is 'mission creep' that distracts from clinical excellence — how do you respond to this criticism?"},
{category:"Policy",scenario:"Private health insurance in Australia is in structural decline, with younger and healthier people dropping cover. This places increasing pressure on the public system.",prompt1:"What are the consequences of this trend, and what should be done about it?",prompt2:"Is a two-tier healthcare system — one for those who can pay, one for those who can't — ethically defensible?",prompt3:"You're Minister for Health and need to announce a policy tomorrow that will reverse this trend within 5 years. What specific intervention do you implement, and how do you sell it to voters who'll pay for it?",prompt4:"Reflect on how your own family's financial situation has shaped your views on healthcare access. How might someone from a completely different economic background see this issue?"},
{category:"Policy",scenario:"The COVID-19 pandemic revealed significant gaps in Australia's public health infrastructure — surveillance systems, supply chains, pandemic planning, and health workforce capacity.",prompt1:"What should Australia have learned from COVID-19, and what systemic changes should have followed?",prompt2:"Why do you think many of those lessons remain unimplemented — and what does that reveal about how health policy is actually made?",prompt3:"You've identified barriers to implementing pandemic lessons — now defend the opposing view: why might deliberate inaction or slow implementation actually be the rational policy choice here?",prompt4:"Take your pandemic preparedness principles and apply them to climate-related health threats — do the same systemic changes work, or does this reveal gaps in your thinking?"},
{category:"Policy",scenario:"There is a strong evidence base for harm reduction approaches to drug policy — needle exchanges, safe injecting facilities, decriminalisation of personal possession. These approaches remain politically contested in Australia.",prompt1:"What is your view on harm reduction as a framework for drug policy?",prompt2:"How do you communicate a position grounded in evidence to a community or patient group that holds strong moral objections to it?",prompt3:"You're now Health Minister and polling shows 70% of voters oppose safe injecting rooms despite the evidence you've presented. Do you proceed with implementation anyway, and how do you justify overriding public opinion?",prompt4:"Think about how you just approached this evidence-versus-values tension. What does your reasoning process reveal about how you weigh scientific data against community sentiment in healthcare decisions?"}
];
